fined as unskilled, 'natural' women’s work) depending on the social context and working conditions in which it occurs. The book challenges feminist dogma and popular myths about housework.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aHousehold employees. 0aHousekeeping. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aJackson, Stevi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311119668840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529201475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529201475/original  a978-3-11-119668-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles